Day 26: DELETE APIs (React + Spring Boot)
Goal

Learn how to delete records from React using Axios and Spring Boot.

What is DELETE?

DELETE removes an existing resource.

Example:

Before:
1 - John
2 - David
3 - Sara

Delete Employee 2

After:
1 - John
3 - Sara
Step 1: Spring Boot DELETE API
EmployeeController.java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/employees")
@CrossOrigin(origins = "http://localhost:5173")
public class EmployeeController {

    @DeleteMapping("/delete/{id}")
    public String deleteEmployee(@PathVariable Long id) {

        System.out.println("Deleting employee: " + id);

        return "Employee Deleted Successfully";
    }
}
Step 2: Create Service Method
EmployeeService.js
import axios from "axios";

const DELETE_API_URL =
    "http://localhost:8070/api/employees/delete";

export const deleteEmployee = (id) => {
    return axios.delete(`${DELETE_API_URL}/${id}`);
}
Step 3: Employee List Component
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import {
    getEmployees,
    deleteEmployee
} from "../../service/EmployeeService";

function EmployeeList() {

    const [employees, setEmployees] = useState([]);

    useEffect(() => {
        loadEmployees();
    }, []);

    const loadEmployees = async () => {

        try {

            const response =
                await getEmployees();

            setEmployees(response.data);

        } catch (error) {

            console.log(error);

        }
    };

    const handleDelete = async (id) => {

        try {

            await deleteEmployee(id);

            alert("Employee Deleted");

            loadEmployees();

        } catch (error) {

            console.log(error);

            alert("Delete Failed");
        }
    };

    return (
        <div>

            <h2>Employees</h2>

            <table border="1">

                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Id</th>
                        <th>Name</th>
                        <th>Department</th>
                        <th>Action</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>

                <tbody>

                    {
                        employees.map(emp => (

                            <tr key={emp.id}>

                                <td>{emp.id}</td>
                                <td>{emp.name}</td>
                                <td>{emp.department}</td>

                                <td>
                                    <button
                                        onClick={() =>
                                            handleDelete(emp.id)
                                        }
                                    >
                                        Delete
                                    </button>
                                </td>

                            </tr>
                        ))
                    }

                </tbody>

            </table>

        </div>
    );
}

export default EmployeeList;
Add Confirmation Dialog
const handleDelete = async (id) => {

    const confirmDelete =
        window.confirm(
            "Are you sure you want to delete?"
        );

    if (!confirmDelete) {
        return;
    }

    try {

        await deleteEmployee(id);

        alert("Deleted Successfully");

        loadEmployees();

    } catch (error) {

        console.log(error);

    }
};
Axios DELETE Syntax
axios.delete(url);

Example:

axios.delete(
    "http://localhost:8070/api/employees/delete/1"
);
Interview Questions
Difference between PUT and DELETE?
PUT	DELETE
Updates data	Removes data
Existing resource	Existing resource
Sends request body	Usually no request body
Why reload data after delete?

To refresh the UI and display the latest data.

loadEmployees();
Real REST API Style

Instead of:

@DeleteMapping("/delete/{id}")

Most projects use:

@DeleteMapping("/{id}")

React:

axios.delete(
    `http://localhost:8070/api/employees/${id}`
);

This follows REST standards.
